What makes a country happy

Introduction and Motivation

Every year the world happiness report is published. The report aims to measure the happiness of people living in the countries of earth as well as the factors that might influence that countries overall happiness. Better understanding what makes a countries happy could give insight into how world leaders could better and more effectively fulfill the needs of the general populace. It also could give an individual an indicator of what countries might be a good place to live or visit should they have that privilege. The following analysis aims to use the data science pipeline in order to identify what relationships exist (if any) between a countries reported happiness score and the countries internal and external factors. We take a look at the world happiness reports from 2015 to 2021 which are records of the data collected from 2014-2020.

Tidy Data

There are a couple issues with the data the way it's been presented to us.

To begin the data is split across seven years. Since were looking for generalized relationships across time were gonna need to combine these tables. Combining the tables will make assessing information easier and more readily available. However we will need to account for time in our analysis later on. So we can record the year as a separate column.

Secondly some years have more Categories than others in order to have a standardized analysis we will only be looking at categories that span all years. More specifically we will be looking at the reported Happiness Score, GDP per Capita, Social Support, Life Expectancy, Freedom, Trust in Government, and Generosity

def std_2015():
    df = dataframes[2015]
    df = df.drop(columns=["Region","Happiness Rank", "Standard Error", "Dystopia Residual"])
    df.columns = columns
    df = df[arranged]
    df["Year"] = 2015
    return df

    df["Year"] = 2016
    return df

Missing data

Since we want to make the final data frame standard across years I've decided to use the 2020's dataset way of labeling the regions. Unfortunately there were a couple countries/territories that weren't a part of the 2020 data so I had to find their regions and fill them out manually.

There was only one row with completely missing data in a column this was the United Arab Emirates Trust in Gov't column. I can only speculate why this particular column was missing. This one row shouldnt significantly affect the rest of the data. Thus I've decided to replace the null value with the mean Trust in Gov't from the region in that year

def get_region(country):
    frame = dataframes[2020].loc[dataframes[2020]["Country name"]==country]
    if frame.size > 0:
        return frame["Regional indicator"].values[0]
    else:
        return missing_regions[country]
        
regions = final_frame.apply(lambda row: get_region(row["Country"]), axis = 1)
final_frame["Region"] = regions
final_frame = final_frame[arranged]
final_frame = final_frame.rename(columns={"Country":"Country/Territory"})

Summary of Columns

Now that our data has been tidied up I offer a brief summary of each columns meaning and what the data for each column represents

Country/Territory This is the country or territory the data for this particular row was collected in.

Region This is the region the country is geographically or culturally a part of.

Year This is the year the data for this particular row was collected on.

Happiness Score This represents the mean happiness of the residents of a particular country. It ranges from 0 to 10 with 0 being the least happy and 10 being the most happy.

GDP per CapitaGDP per capita is a country's economic output divided by its population.

Social SupportRepresents how well residents feel supported by friends, family members and social programs

Life ExpectancyReports a countries life expectancy on a given year on a standardized scale

FreedomReports residents satisfaction in their ability to make choices that impact their lives

GenerosityReports how likely residents were to donate to charity

Trust in Gov'tReports residents perception of corruption in their respective governments

As expected our correlation heat map shows that there is a correlation between the happiness score of a country and its GDP per capita, Social Support, Life Expectancy, and Freedom. What was interesting is that it also showed that there is also a positive correlation between a countries GDP per capita and its Social Support, and Life Expectancy. This also makes sense as people in wealthier countries can afford to support each other and might have access to better health care.

Even though there might be some correleation between GDP, Social Support, and Life Expectancy we are still going to treat them as independent when making our model for Happiness Score

The correlation doesn't necessarily imply causation moreover these factors individually might influence happiness score in a way that just using the gdp might not be able to.

Machine Learning

Now that we have established there is probably a linear relationship between the happiness score of a country and its GDP per capita, Social Support, Life Expectancy, and Freedom. It's time to train a model so that given, GDP per capita, Social Support, Life Expectancy, and Freedom for a hypothetical country we can predict the happiness score for that country.

We will be using a sklearns linear regression module in order to form a multiple regression model for our data

The first thing we need to do is to split our data into training and testing subsets and the code below will perform this task

In [16]:
train, test = train_test_split(final_frame, test_size=0.2)

After splitting our data we create a linear model using our training data and test it against our training data. Then we get some metrics in order to see how well our data performed in predicting happiness scores given our inputs

In [17]:
X_train = train[["GDP per Capita", "Social Support", "Life Expectancy", "Freedom"]]
X_test = test[["GDP per Capita", "Social Support", "Life Expectancy", "Freedom"]]
y_train = train["Happiness Score"]
y_test = test["Happiness Score"]
regr = linear_model.LinearRegression()
regr.fit(X_train, y_train)

#predictions using our model
y_train_pred = regr.predict(X_train)
y_test_pred = regr.predict(X_test)

#This gives us some metrics on how well our model did
def regression_results(y_true, y_pred):
    # Regression metrics
    explained_variance=metrics.explained_variance_score(y_true, y_pred)
    mean_absolute_error=metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred) 
    mse=metrics.mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred) 
    mean_squared_log_error=metrics.mean_squared_log_error(y_true, y_pred)
    median_absolute_error=metrics.median_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)
    r2=metrics.r2_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print('explained_variance: ', round(explained_variance,4))    
    print('mean_squared_log_error: ', round(mean_squared_log_error,4))
    print('r2: ', round(r2,4))
    print('MAE: ', round(mean_absolute_error,4))
    print('MSE: ', round(mse,4))
    print('RMSE: ', round(np.sqrt(mse),4))
    print("")
          
regression_results(y_train, y_train_pred)
regression_results(y_test, y_test_pred)

Analysis of results

So we created our model and predicted values based on our training set and our test set. Then I ran some metrics in order to see how well our model did in predicting values. The two most important metrics above are the explained_variance score, and the r2 score. In both scores a 1.0 is the best and the model is progressively worse the lower it goes

Explained variation measures the proportion to which a mathematical model accounts for the variation (dispersion) of a given data set.

r2 score, is the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable(s).

In both scores our model perfomed at approximately .75 which I believe is acceptable in showing that our model is accurate in predicting the happiness score of a country given the "GDP per Capita", "Social Support", "Life Expectancy", and "Freedom" scores of a country

Final Thoughts

Human beings are complicated and trying to predict human behavior or predict human fulfillment is very difficult to do. We are influenced by many different things which can affect our mood and behavior in a variety of ways. So this tutorial isn't claiming to have found a way to predict general human happiness. However in the introduction I stated that a goal of this tutorial and the subsequent analysis that followed was to identify what relationships exist between a countries happiness score and its internal and external factors.

In our exploratory stage after plotting our data we were able to observe a positive linear relationship between Happiness Score and GDP per Capita, Happiness Score and Social Support, Happiness Score and Life Expectancy, and Happiness Score and Freedom.

Using our observations as a guide we were able to formulate a model that was able to accurately predict the overall happiness score of a country given "GDP per Capita", "Social Support", "Life Expectancy", and "Freedom".
